Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - an annual inflation rate of 3.1% was recorded after the 2.6% in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been expected to reach only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, British, and Canadian Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the benchmark interest rate. At its discretion, the interest-rate cut would favor rising commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment to create an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the throwback: inflation needs to be “eliminated ” in order to avoid later action.
At 3.3%, the inflation rate reached a record high in Germany in November of 12% year; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6% to 4.1%.
The increased food and energy prices are responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone.
The MATIF and wheat quotes rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in prices for edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world price of crude oil this year rose by 52 percent - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% in 2008 to 2.5%, but it is expected to decline to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts expect an inflation rate of 3 percent for the next 3 months, but estimate the average annual rate of 2.1 percent.
Experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
