Many places are saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overloading of the personnel - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the control of the infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the Traumatology Department of the János Hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection.
The injured of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation could not be performed because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, senior physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark digit is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin and oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA caused infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) usually react well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
If, however, the remedies are dosed too high or used improperly, the well-corresponding bacteria produce antibiotics resistant, which quickly spread in the hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older patients or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the daily illness.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA does not exist only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the care staff carries rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are hospitalized, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the containment of the emergence or the spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and retirement homes, the hospitals should examine the patients supplied and isolate MRSA infected immediately.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practiced so frequently.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this examination on the part of the state health insurance company.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate application of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotics and therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always respected by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, among outpatient or primary patients, microbiological sampling is even more rare.
Gespart is used for disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted by one patient to another by carers.
This is precisely why washing hands or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted through droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient in the local hospitals.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are lined up, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately in the financially less well-off hospitals it even occurs that disinfectants are saved, there are few carers, many patients - all factors that favour the development of infections.
Such infections are demonstrably far less common there, or can be stopped the further spread of the pathogen, where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA to get a grip on infections causes the health insurance companies enormous costs, therefore they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - according to published data, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
