Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three loan agreements worth EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday, with the aim of providing education, transport and environmental protection for infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for financing transport and environmental projects implemented through grants from the Cohesion Fund.
The amount of €150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be devoted to the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary and the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later on as part of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly be channelled into research and development programmes at Debrecen University.
At the meeting also the U-Bahn line 4 was discussed.
It was agreed that as soon as Hungary clarified the details of the EU's financing of the railway, the original Treaty and any modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects worth EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest rates are EURIBOR and the loan will be provided by the EIB with a period of 8 years, free of commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe looks attentively at the Balkan state, which was rarely mentioned before.
What, where, and who buys the EU's still cheapest market, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re / Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most desirable pavement for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the Renner, however, real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimations of Re / Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country was also likely to attract investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favourable area of Russe has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive offers - commercial and office space offer highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfer paradises, thus attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter season as well as in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also prospective buyers from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while Russian buyers are mainly present at the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re / Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle buy either revitalized properties for 50 €100,000, or rundown houses for 5 €15,000, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are decisive for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group is made up of businessmen who invest with the aim of a medium- to long-term increase in value.
Real estate in the capital, however, is becoming more and more expensive due to ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, while real estate prices are lowest in Bulgaria, there has been an annual price increase of 21% over the past five years.
The price of real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the Six Hungarian Percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss the Bali roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signalled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be prepared to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25% by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question at the conference is whether developed countries are prepared to provide both financial and technological support to developing countries in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement has also been reached on support for developing countries.
The Kyoto Protocol ’ s adjustment fund is to be managed by a 16-member council, probably at the UN ’ s Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the “Piac és Profit ”.
Hungary ’ s Six Percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's commitment to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that by 2020, the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (as measured by 1990 levels), regardless of whether the "post-2012 agreement" would be successful, or not. Indeed, the Union would be prepared to commit itself to a 30% reduction, as far as other major industrial countries in the world, or developing countries, are also prepared to fulfil their obligations in every way and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the states that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its then 15 member states.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985 – 87 – a target that the country will fulfil, as can be seen in the Ministry of the Environment press release.
The deployment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be finalised within two years, otherwise it would certainly only enter into force after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a renewed, international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international UN Scientific Climate Change Committee, awarded with the Nobel Peace Prize in its latest report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and increasing the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 ° C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to increase their popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special units stationed in Afghanistan have been downloading videos of operations conducted against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The thumbnails mounted on helmets are controlled at the Air Force Base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political Embassy Unavoidable
Soldiers of the Air Force have already contributed 139 such shots, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Department of Defense was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Department of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Operations in Afghanistan
Initially, the Air Force has published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign missions.
Such publicized propaganda is almost free of charge compared to conventional television commercials, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans Advertise With game
But the army also has to fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully worked, censored shots, also create it in the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are at most talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos have already been loaded onto the platform from the war locations in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British have only recently discovered this "genus" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "Amerikas Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier in the context of a more or less life-like simulation.
