holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of reallocating the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year gives us fewer such days.
In the EU and in America, too, something else is understood as' holiday '.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and working days.
Working days are usually ecclesiastical holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15, commemorating the revolution of 1848, and October 23, the anniversary of the 1956 revolution.
On 20 August, the foundation of the state is celebrated, on 1 May, the work is celebrated, and on 1 and 2 November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "postponement of work" has proven itself in cases where we would work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends is, however, that we have to work very well on the Saturday before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be processed, is fixed for many years by the Minister of Labour in its own regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants.
Only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays, are excluded.
This year, the working regulations are only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from the 24th of December, life will remain in this country, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year ’ s Eve will take time compensation, or the holiday that has been specially cancelled.
Next year, more holidays will fall into the middle of the week or the end of the week, so there will be fewer re-allocations for the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 can be a rest day.
The second relocation is related to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October, Friday, 24 October will have to be processed in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely dedicated to the holidays, after everything will be up and running from the 24th of December, even if New Year ’ s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
