Cuba - most beautiful island of the Caribbean
For visitors it is really an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will be fulfilled if you choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
Only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Nacional Hotel was built at the end of the 20th century.
One of the leaders of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, had it built, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during prohibition) was gladly seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, skyscrapers were growing, and cars across the wide boulevards were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of the show business and politicians from all over America signed their signatures.
And today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can also leave your autograph.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can enjoy cocktails as desired.
And the cult cars of the fifties are still driving around in Havana, because the once imported igulis and fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
May Havana, especially its oldest part, have come down strongly, nowhere can you find in the vicinity as many wonderful colonial sights as just here.
Other places are just being cleaned out, for example Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings urgently needed money, there was a green light for this development.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a Marotte, which is unique in the world and attracts above all railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam- and diesel-powered narrow gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet was not renewed for decades, and so one sees there cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long since been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
The most important places do not leave out the majority of visitors to Cuba.
You don't have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
It is worth mentioning that there is a museum in the already mentioned Hemingway estate, whose visit should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Viñales valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form you can meet him if you visit one of the cigar factories of Havana.
Perhaps it seems interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spaniards had colonized the island.
Glory and wealth brought her trade in slaves and sugar.
The wealth embodied itself in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, situated between the sea and the Escambray mountains, is such a remote place that in the 1950s there was no road connecting the area with the rest of the country.
This insulation helped to keep it unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon time for Trinidad, then it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón beach or the "valley of sugar factories".
In the evening you should go to the Casa de la Música, which livens up after the darkness, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful of the island.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads that lead from Guantánamo must overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
UNESCO recorded this eastern outpost of Cuba in its World Heritage List thanks to the untouched nature there.
Here the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the present hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra and Maestra mountains, the pork power and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this one could write many pages.
But, as you say, look better with your own eyes.
