For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented today to a court in Khartoum.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been indicted for insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days imprisonment and expulsion by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman was accused of having allowed six- to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name Mahomet, although any representation of the Islamic prophet is forbidden.
It would have deserved to be whipped.
After parents of pupils complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Education, the 54 year-old primary school teacher, who worked at the Unity High School of Khartoum, was picked up at home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports headmaster Robert Boules.
Finally, as the class votes, 20 of 23 children elect Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear himself did not carry a shield with this name, but the problem is quite simply that the presentation of the Islamic prophet is regarded as an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who is teaching at the same school in Sudan, said that he knows them well, and that she would never have done anything to bring them closer to a religious belief, I only regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is just an innocent mistake.
An opinion that many students of the teacher share, who describe them as being very attentive to their students and as a person who never speaks in class about religion.
Consider that the first name Mohammed is at the same time also the second name most frequently given in Great Britain, for which 14 different spellings exist in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is regarded as a kind of homage to the prophets (often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
