According to testimonies, in the city of Lahore in the east of the country, about 2,000 lawyers demonstrating against the emergency measures had been injured by the tear gas grenades used by the police there.
They then threw stones to hurt the police.
At least 350 lawyers were temporarily arrested.
There were similar scenarios in Karachi and Rawalpindi, where police attacked and injured lawyers.
Several would have been temporarily arrested.
In Islamabad, the lawyers of the Supreme Court ’ s bar have called for a general strike and announced demonstrations as a result of a wave of about 500 arrests by opposition activists, advocates of human rights and lawyers during the weekend.
Monday morning, the roads leading to the Supreme Court were closed to prevent the assembly.
Further demonstrations would have taken place in Multan (center) and Peshawar (northeast).
On Monday, the lawyers ’ movement received the support of the religious parties united in the powerful alliance Muttahida Majlis and Amal, whose president called on the population to send flowers to the judges who spoke out against the emergency, and to those who took an oath before Musharraf.
Musharraf ’ s promise no longer applies
Pakistan's Supreme Court is directly affected by the special measure announced on Saturday evening.
In the following days he had to take a position on the legality of President Musharraf's re-election in a direct ballot on 6 October.
The chairman of the court, Iftikhar Mohammed Chaudhry, was relieved and replaced.
All that we represent is illegal, anti-constitutional, and contrary to the decisions of the Supreme Court, the magistrate of the newspaper The News said.
Pervez Musharraf ’ s promise to surrender the command to the army and become a civilian president no longer applies since the emergency was invoked, said on Monday the Deputy Minister for Information Tariq Azeem.
He was expected to surrender his military uniform until 15 November, the date on which his first term as president ends.
The Deputy Minister for Information also confirmed that the January elections could be postponed.
Moreover, the Pakistani government denied the persistent rumours in the country that President Musharraf would have been assigned residence by his deputy commander.
