Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to carry out the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector indispensable for the continuation of scientific work at the station.
A daring exit that, due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools designed by astronauts to carry out the repair, has achieved several records.
The problem occurred on Wednesday, when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the Discovery space shuttle, a large cylindrical part that was soon to accommodate European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module laboratories.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was thus to implement a 17.5 ton power generation module via solar panels, which was already on the ISS, in order to bring it into its final position.
After moving it, the crew decided to restructure the solar panels of the module, with a span of 76 metres.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be opened like accordions, was damaged by a clamped cable on a length of about one meter
The restructuring was stopped so as not to damage the collector any more.
The astronauts who were originally supposed to leave the Discovery space shuttle for a control gear and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was incorrect were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was selected to walk around at the end of the 30 metre long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle attached to that of the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skilful, he has a well developed torso and long arms.
The 46 year-old trained doctor was therefore selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After he had thoroughly assessed the damage, he severed the faulty cable and fixed some kind of rails on the damaged spot.
He was supported by a second spacewalker who remained near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey bat wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar panels that generate several hundred volts, the astronauts had designed and built on board the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully folded before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation, before today seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery to presumably take the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
