A heavy souvenir
After being treated confidentially for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, have not been seen until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. by requesting a former victim or his relatives.
In May 2006, the eleven state administrators, including Germany, France, Israel and the US, agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable them to carry out research, especially on deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of the forced laborers, explains Reto Meister, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Such as alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The list of inmates in the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for them to compensate.
Even today in Bad Arolsen more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of personal enquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One should expect nothing fundamentally new in these documents, Pr. Wolfgang Benz, director of the research center for anti-Semitism of the Technische Universität Berlin, had declared 2006.
The EU and India want a free trade agreement in 2008.
Mutual trade between India and Europe is already reaching EUR 60 billion a year.
The EU is India's main trading partner, accounting for 18% of its external trade.
European Trade Minister Peter Mandelson and his Indian counterpart, Kamal Nath, said that the European Union and India hope to sign a free trade agreement in 2008.
The EU Foreign Ministers gave the European Commission the green light last April to open negotiations with a view to signing free trade agreements (ALE) with India, South Korea and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (Asean). Mutual trade between India and Europe is already reaching EUR 60 billion a year.
The EU is India's first trading partner, accounting for 18% of its external trade.
The EU is also its first foreign investor, but according to the figures of the European Commission, India is only the EU's ninth trading partner.
A free trade pact will greatly advance the two economies and India would improve its access to a market of 450 million wealthy Europeans, confirmed Peter Mandelson.
Europe is the first or second market for the ten products most frequently exported by India, the European Commissioner said. Asian and European giants exchange goods worth EUR 47 billion and services worth EUR 10 billion annually, Daniéle Smadja, President of the European Commission's delegation in New Delhi, said this week and regrets that mutual trade has not yet exhausted its potential. EU and India will meet on Friday for their eighth diplomatic meeting in New Delhi, with Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and European Commission President José Manuel Durao Barrosso.
(Source AFP)
The Bank of England takes note of the concern and offers £10 billion for five weeks
The Bank of England expressed concern on Thursday about curbing the current recurring concern about the credit terms and announced an offer of £10 billion with a basic interest rate of 5.75% for five weeks, an offer with an unusual maturity.
In order to alleviate fears that conditions on the financial market will be particularly hard at the end of the year, and to give banks greater certainty about the way in which they are to organise their liquidity positions at that time, the Bank intends to offer a significant portion of its savings during the conservation period, which begins on 6 December, in the form of an open market operation for five weeks, it states in a communication.
The Bank further states that on 6 December at 12.15 GMT, £10 billion (EUR 14 billion) will be put into circulation, at the basic tax rate and only until 10 January.
This is apparently the first time that the BoE has circulated liquidities for five weeks in an open market operation.
This usually happens for a week.
In its communication, BoE adds that it is ready to take further measures to obtain the interest rates of interbank lending, which vary from day to day, with their basic interest rate.
The interbank interest rate varied from day to day on Wednesday was 5.829%.
The three-month interest rate has swung to 6.6%, slightly higher since September 18.
Since the start of the summer ’ s financial crisis, the sums circulated by the Bank of England have been coupled with penalties that prevented banks from claiming them.
According to some rumours, reinforced by the development of the pound price as opposed to the euro, many preferred to sign for the sums circulated by the European Central Bank at more advantageous interest rates and with safer discretion
