Pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to invade; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals this is not particularly slippery.
No nobility titles seem to be sold, no politician pays Paris hotel bills, no extramarital toes have been sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has veiled donations to the British ruling Labour Party for more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something without which the contested Gordon Brown would have done well.
When two months ago the Prime Minister withdrew from calling for an election, insulting the British intelligence in a stupid way by claiming that opinion polls had not affected this decision, there was hope that he would offer a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly acute leader of the Liberal Democrats, put it, Stalin ’ s once feared Brown has evolved into Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a troubled bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Worse thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have brought business associations against the government.
The loss of personal data by the tax authorities of 25 million people showed unimaginable administrative bottlenecks.
A trio of retired generals started a Upper House uprising in protest against cuts in military spending: being military ministers, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are many donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labours General Secretary (and her former head of fulfilment) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown irrevocably sets off.
Yet governments can reach a turning point that makes it impossible to govern.
Neither do people like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their scepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he does not even need to be involved for a long time, this delay is over: the public service begins to leak; cabinet ministers begin to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In one way, Brown ’ s position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction documents, for example, are related to decisions made by Brown as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if it wasn ’ t directly involved in Blair ’ s misfortunes – as with the long “money for aristocracy ” investigation of political party financing – voters may assume that it was.
Nevertheless, Brown ’ s situation is not quite as bad as it looks
The failures are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely dizzy.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown ’ s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The new commitment to political donations is a good example.
The garboesque Abraham, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not wish public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be the case, but he was not entitled to the decision.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he would have known about Abraham ’ s agreement, but not that it is illegal, will of course have to ask some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labours ’ s main financial collector, who was told about the odd donations in October.
But so far, Brown has not been involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these confusion, although most of the payments were made after his takeover in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half of the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he diluted this determination by grasping a known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to make the measure full, by a bishop retired and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law was broken, it is one thing for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things that Mr Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent public standards committee, which has been unoccupied for six months, and moving forward with a thorough reform of political party financing.
That would require Labour hardliners to cooperate with conservatives and possibly give up the special financial relationship with trade unions - bitter pills for a party member like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through unquestionable righteousness and solid competence.
Cardsharks
Is America ’ s credit card market caught up in the credit crisis?
When blood is in the water, it is only natural that dorsal fins swirl around excitedly.
Now that America ’ s real estate market is raging, predators are targeting the country ’ s credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded credit spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both bookings and default rates that measure the share of loans that are either unrecoverable or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it has withdrawn a $1.4 billion fee from its US consumer financing, partly because of the weakness of credit card holders.
It is nevertheless too early to panic.
Losses and failures are still low.
According to rating agency Moody, the third-quarter default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in US private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt case of bankruptcy applications, which in turn account for a large proportion of card losses; the number of applications (and hence default fees) would rise again, whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
Industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of its debt consumers pay off each month
and confidence in credit card based securities is fairly strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured financing.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research company, expects that the output volumes for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
Direct infectious channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: it is more likely that consumers take credit card debt, now that home loans dry out.
The card exhibitors, however, look at the flow of money instead of capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the creditworthiness of the borrower.
They can even be beneficial for card exhibitors.
Incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates fall when real estate is less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt is becoming more important under the repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
"We will not wake up one day and completely reassess the loans," says Gary Perlin, Capital Ones ’ main financial adviser.
Even if a sudden undercover crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustainable downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and a credit cut push America into recession, industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
