Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the proof - it felt electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: The lightnings on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primordial soups" theory, lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been in the very early history," explains Sean Solomon from the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there is hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus is perhaps the devil's twin of the earth, but it is a twin," said Russel.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in size and size, has taken such a completely different development, is the basic question of Esa's mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus's research, since no probe was on its way to explore this planet since the early nineties.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighbouring planet with the Earth are larger than initially assumed," says Esa.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the earthly winter hemisphere, writes a research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also called Morning or Evening Star, circles around the sun in almost 225 days.
But it is much slower about itself: a Venus day lasts 243 days on earth.
Although Venus hardly resembles Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
